<dl id="n54110b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54110b">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54110b"> 110(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cold of Medina &amp; heat / of Mecca merits Paradise <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54110b"><li>FW 316.14 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n54110b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n54110b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54110b">MS BL 47479-172</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:265 <a name="mad6" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mad6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad6.htm#n54110b">Draft: II.3&sect;1.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The valley of Meccah is hot and sultry, while Med&#299;nah, standing on the edge of a high tableland, is exposed to bitter winds and storms. Rainy weather prevails during half the year, and the outskirts of the city are often flooded. The winters are intensely cold, and Mohammed once declared that &ldquo;he who patiently endures <mark>the cold of Med&#299;nah and the heat of Meccah merits a reward in Paradise</mark>.&rdquo; <small> Edith Holland, <a name="EHSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EHSM"><cite title="source">The Story of Mohammed</cite></a> (1914) 97</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
